segments.text: They later moved to the North Gate area and occupied a building that had been moved from Victoria Air Force Base, a chapel from that base.
The other First Baptist Church was at the North Gate, A&M Methodist Church, St. Mary's Catholic Church.
Later churches came in were Church of Christ, and most of those have relocated from the North Gate area.
Did your family, were they church attenders?
My father at the First Baptist Church was on the board of trustees there.
They originally organized from a building on the campus and met, I believe, in the E.E.
building lecture room and then later moved off to the campus.
Reverend R.L.
Brown was the first member.
pastor of that church and he would come by and see Papa for church activities while we lived on the campus there.
Now I'm guessing that during that era most of the campus families
were mainline Protestants.
Is that?
I would, I'm trying to, and I'm going to say I know a number of Baptist families that went to church in Bryan at First Baptist Church.
And I guess, and there were a number of Methodists.
The Episcopal Church
was not organized.
It later was organized and had a chapel across from Duncan Field on Jersey Street.
George Bush.
George Bush Drive.
And there was a big delegation of Catholic students, though, that were served through St. Joseph Church in Bryan.
And then St. Mary's.
Where was that?
St. Mary's.
Do you remember during those growing up years any Jewish member of the faculty or staff?
Yes, sir.
Mr. Halperin in the math department was a little man.
And I believe he was Jewish.
So I presume then he went all the way to Bryan to worship.
He must have because they had, well, later they did have the Hillel Foundation south of campus.
But at that time when I was growing up, they didn't have it.
Do you by chance remember any comparatively outspoken non-believer?
Was there any?
What I'm assuming is that in that era, religion was one of the comparative normal parts of the routine of the campus.
Of campus life, that's true.
No, sir, I really don't.
You know, Mr. Cashin was head of the YMCA.
M.L.
Cashin was a
first secretary that I remember, and then Mr.
Gay followed him.
Gordon Gay.
Please describe your memory of Mr. Cashin.
He was a fine gentleman.
He was known as a true believer.
And one of the stories about Red Cashin is he asked his daddy, why did you always pray for A&M after every prayer you read from here at home?
Getting mixed up, you know, all men with A&M.
Now the Cashin boys, are they your contemporaries?
Jimmy is three or four years
younger than I am, and Mason must be about 10 years younger, something like that.
All right, now, you called him Mason.
Mason Lee.
Yes.
That was what ML called Red.
When did he become known as Red?
Well, he was always red-headed.
I know.
So as a little bitty?
Yeah, as a kid, he was Red.
Did you have a nickname?
Uh, D.B., uh...
And then Dusty Butt got fitted because of our stature.
That was Papa's nickname.
And I assumed that, but outside of that.
All right.
Did your dad, somebody told me that they thought sometimes when he would erase the board, he would unconsciously kind of rub his hand on the side of his trousers and maybe get a little chalk dust.
Yeah.

ah i don't i don't recall that no i really don't but i do recall one professor that i had and that was when i went to a m and that was mr bob lyle in the math department that he would come in neatly dressed with the tie and shirt and then he would start writing on the board and by the time the

session was over his tie would be down and chalk dust would be all over him and the board would be full did he have a nickname i don't think so but he was he was a good teacher yes ma'am let's go back to elementary school
Were there any important extracurricular activities that you remember from your elementary school days?
The extracurricular activities centered around what we called the Interscholastic League County Meets.
Declamation contests, softball, track,
They were the spring event, actually.
Now, this was in addition to organized football and basketball.
It didn't go, it wasn't near the program that there is today.
It was on an interscholastic league meet where all of the county schools would have a meet at a certain place and they would have competitions.
And I remember specifically
that I would participate in declamation contests.
And one of my main adversaries was John Lawrence III in Bryan.
And we met numerous times at those particular meets.
Were there many associations between you elementary college station kids and the Bryan kids?
Yes.
We would go to the same dances.
We were known as a crowd.
That meant your age group was a crowd.
And Bryan College Station would go together.
Surely would.
Of course, the main activity would be in Bryan.
But we would have dances.
And we would attend.
And the College Station group was included.
And in Bryan were included also some College Station dancers.
All right, still in the elementary years, where did your mom do her grocery shopping?
At Luke and Charlie's at the North Gate, which you could walk out of our back door and walk across the railroad and the street, and you could go get a loaf of bread if it was needed.
But that was the main.
And then there was also a community grocery store on campus.
But it actually, it had delivery.
And one of the delivery men was named Graves, and at one time he drove a little horse-drawn wagon.
Did the college operate that community store?
It was operated by someone else.
I don't think it was operated directly by the college.
But the college did have milk delivery in the morning from the F&B station.
And then the creamery also had dairy products.
But we did shop in, I mean grocery shopping was at the North Gate.
Let's see, did your, your family had a car as your memory begins?
We didn't have a car until 1935 or so and we used the
Bryan College Station, what did they call that traction company?
The trolley?
It was the trolley first and then it later became a bus line after the trolley went out.
Was the trolley within your memory or had it stopped?
I remember riding it on occasion vividly, but I know where the station was behind the chapel, the campus chapel.
now and it entered not far from us where we live down at the but where the mr. boy it's house was on the corner there where the campus can't think of that

theater uh movie was and that it came onto the campus then and rode around about to the chapel but uh i'm more memory of the uh bus lines about how frequently did the on the hours on the hour do you remember what what the fair was something like uh
25 cents round trip, 10 or 15 cents one way, something like that.
And downtown Bryan was a busy place.
Absolutely.
That was the center of business activity, you see, in most of the stores.
The bus line went to just a block from Main Street at the old, well, the Eagle Building at one time was there as the newest thing closest to it.
And it was just on, I forgot the name of it, but it was just a block from Main Street.
Describe during the pre-World War II days, in the late 30s, describe downtown Bryan on a Saturday afternoon.
Quite busy.
The movies were, it had three movies.
They had the Queen, the Dixie, and the Palace.
All right there in one block, two on one side of the street and one on the other.
And it was quite a place.
Most students would go to town at that time in shock.
And everybody, all local citizens as well, would go.
I remember one thing, Allen Academy would not go to town on Saturday.
That's why they gave those students off on Monday.
when nobody was downtown because it was so busy.
They would permit, they would give their students Monday off instead of Saturday to prevent any kind of conflict or anything like that.
And it was more advantageous for them because there were fewer folks.
What was the five and ten cent downtown?
F.W.
Woolworth and Perry Brothers.
And of course, Woolworth later became in the center block there.
But of course, it's been closed for a number of years.
Menswear?
A&M Waldrop.
A&M Waldrop and Company.
They had a college store and a brine store.
Waldrop sold uniforms primarily out at college, and they were at the North Gate.
And then they had the downtown store was their main store.
Ladieswear.
As I recall, the first ladieswear was the Smart Shop.
That was...
I can't think of who organized that, but that was the first ladies ready to wear.
And then there was Eugene Edge on the corner.
And if a family went out to eat, where would they go?
They would primarily go to the Aggieland Inn, which was on the campus and had a nice
restaurant, cafe, because it was run by the mess hall.
And that would be a place you could go to eat.
Now, as your memory begins, was Mr. Duncan in charge of food?
The mess hall.
Describe him.
He was a very impressive-looking gentleman, gray-haired,
And I remember him, I guess, primarily as being a devoted mason, and on certain occasions he would put his Knight Templar uniform on and go to Bryan for communications.
The Sebesa Dining Hall was a center not only of eating but of social events I know.
Did you and your family ever eat at Sebesa when you were in high school?
Only on special occasions there would be, but I don't recall any until after
I went to A&M.
All right, back to your elementary days.
Are there some teachers that you would like to mention and express your gratitude for them?
Yes, I remember one in particular, Mrs. Henrietta C. Doak, Dr. Doak's wife, who lived on campus with the Boltons, which was just walking distance to
grammar school.
She taught me in the seventh grade and was an excellent teacher.
She later had the opportunity to teach my children at Sol Ross Elementary School in Bryan after she had retired once from Consolidated.
And had gone to Snook, I think, and retired there, and then had come back to teaching.
She was a long-time teacher.
And Dr. Doak was head of the biology department.
And we lived in the same area with them in South Oakwood.
And I remember he was a great gardener and would give us some of his
of production.
We enjoyed that.
But she was a fine teacher.
Then another high school teacher was Mrs. Ethel Walton Burgess.
She taught English and she was, I had a very hard time getting a acceptable grade at home in English.
But she was a good teacher.
You had a built-in English teacher.
I had one.
It was always looking over my shoulder, but she was very good.
She taught English in high school for any number of years.
In high school, describe that A&M Consolidated High School in your four years.
As I recall, when I went to high school in 35, 36, the superintendent was Mr. James H. Sykes, who was elated over the fact that he had hired two
recent graduates from Southwestern University.
One was I.D.
Hoke and the other one was Thomas Ferguson.
To come, Mr. Hoke taught social studies and Mr. Ferguson taught science.
And I think, and they were to inaugurate a football team.
And I think the first team played about four games, and then later it gradually increased as the years progressed.
And Mr. Hope left someplace, and Mr. Ferguson later became on the faculty at A&M.
One other teacher that I recall was Caroline Mitchell, who taught math,

in in high school and she was an excellent teacher now this is jw mitchell's daughter this is the caroline mitchell that you and i both knew and she worked in the registrar's office describe her please as a teacher her personality she was the most patient person you ever saw

and she was an excellent teacher and she would explain it and then if you uh... grasp it and reported it to back to her she would qualify you she was an excellent teacher as well as Mr. Mitchell he was known for his uh... math contest when he was in A&M among the students he uh...
inaugurated he called them in honor of mr. they called him mr. Bobby Smith a famous math teacher at A&M and he would have these calculus contests and all and they would award watches and
to the winners and all, and he would coach those students.
And he started that at A&M.
That was Mr. Mitchell.
Well, Caroline later taught at other schools in the state and then came back to A&M as the
academic advisor for the transfer students, something like that.
In those four high school years, as you recall, what kind of mathematics courses did you all take?
We had Algebra I, II, Plain Geometry, and then senior year, Solid Geometry and Trigonometry.
That's exactly what I had.
Those were the courses.
And what sciences?
general science, biology for the first two years.
And then if you were really inclined, you could take physics.
junior and senior, or junior or senior.
And as I recall, our physics class had opportunity to go adjacent to the physics building on campus to use the laboratory.
What about chemistry?
No chemistry was taught.
No chemistry.
And with your father being an English teacher, what English courses do you, how much?
We had four years of English.
One, two, and, well, four.
So that by and large, everybody at A&M Consolidated High School then took what we would now call a college prep curriculum.
Exactly.
Sixteen credits were required for entrance to A&M or any other state school, I think.
Now, if you and any of your buddies were wanting to create some mischief when you were in high school, what would that consist of?
Maybe rolling the trash can down the stairs.
That was done on numerous occasions because we had
Stairs, no elevators, and it was just a two-story building and a big trash can and all.
But there wasn't really a great deal of that.
Do you remember anybody, any of the high school kids attempting to smoke?
Oh, I think that, oh, they had access.
Well, I remember I had an occasion, too, when...
some of these rural children introduced me at the Christmas tree to chewing tobacco.
It was quite an occasion.
It was remembered and never tried again.
Did your stomach reject?
It did.
That's a terrible feeling.
As far as you recall, what were the either clearly defined or clearly not defined but clearly understood rules of conduct that you got from your parents?
Well, the rule at home was you observe student.
And if you got in trouble at school while you had a

second opportunity to redeem yourself, if you want to call it that, but it also meant you had second punishment if you had to stay in school for whatever reason at all, otherwise you had to answer then to the family situation.
Where in those years, where did someone get an alcoholic drink in Brazos County?
In those years, as I recall, the closest to A&M were two places.
There was Uncle Ed Hardlicker on Weldon Road.
who naturally made, believe it or not, once he said, believe it or not, Ed Hardaker, College Station, Texas, sells soft drinks.
But at the East Gate was, there was a cafe over there that had beer.
Of course, that came in during
First administration between 32 to 36, something like that.
Now, the county was dry for whiskey, and you would have to go across to Burleson County to buy anything.
In that era, was it called Whiskey Bridge?
Whiskey Bridge was out 60, as I recall, and a little store just across the river there.
But was it called that then?
It was.
It was a bridge and then...
There was another one across Highway 21.
And I've forgotten the name of that.
Avalon.
That was the Avalon Club.
I think they had package stores out there.
And then later, the Smetana Precinct in Brazos County was one of the first to go wet.
And then naturally, it increased.
The whole county became.
All right, let's go back to football.
You mentioned that football started when you were in ninth, 10th grade?
The 8th grade, 9th, 10th, 11th were our four senior years.
So I think it started that year or the next year, but as I recall it was in 36 or 37.
And where did you all play your Kyle Field practice field?
Not the main field, but the practice field.
They would permit us to go down there.
What about baseball and basketball games?
Where were they played?
Basketball games from high school were played in the little gym that they called, it was a big
wooden gym and then sometimes for the bigger games they would get the main floor in the old DeWare Field House.
But there used to be a little gym next where the swimming pool is and of course that's gone now.
There was a wooden gymnasium there that had handball courts and a wooden floor, I mean a basketball court too.
And we would go down there because it was usually open.
They couldn't very well close it.
And one of our favorite pastimes was playing on that wooden floor what we called Tin Can Shinny on roller skates.
It's kind of a modified hockey game.
Mm-hmm.
And Mr. Ashford, who was in charge of the athletic facilities there, would come in one door and we would go out the other door when he wanted to terminate our activities.
Where did you and your buddies go swimming?
Go where?
Swimming.
There was a swimming pool in the old YMCA building, in the basement there before it became a bowling alley.
There was a swimming pool there before they had the main swimming pool at... P.L.
Downs.
P.L.
Downs, an auditorium there.
We would go to that YMCA building,

all right now let's move you up to college do you recall there ever being any doubt as to where you would go to college no doubt whatsoever the only doubt i had was would i be able to make the grades that first semester and that was my main concern because i knew where i would go and of course it in those times uh
The, on the horizon was war and all and you just, that's where you would go to school.
Where did you, where did you live as a student?
I lived at home part of the time and then towards the junior year while I went to the dormitory and lived in the dormitory.
Right.
Please describe what it was like to be a home residing freshman in the Corps.
Well, I had a lot of friends.
I made friends because I took liberal arts, and there was a core of us liberal arts students.
That means pre-law students or economics majors or things like that because you had no business school or anything like that.
Well, you did have the Agriculture Administration, but I made friends my first semester, and I was always, I enjoyed inviting them over to the house, and we'd study.
around the dining room table for a quiz, a letter quiz or a final quiz.
And I made lots of contacts in that I maintain and still know many of those fellows today.
So you enrolled as a freshman in the fall of 39.
So you're enrolling as a freshman as the war is beginning in Europe.
Correct.
The, now I'm assuming,

that with your father looking over your shoulder, that you had no grade troubles, did anybody ever give you, any sophomore or junior or senior, ever give you a hard time because you were a faculty brat?
No, I don't recall it.
They would pump me for information quite a bit, and I was fairly well accepted, and I would take some fatherless...
